@Abu Hajaar serious? Yes it is, for hundreds(if not thousands ) of years women have been restricted to certain types of task by law or by social reproduction, and while they are equally capable than men in intellectual tasks.
Even after this video do you think there is no problem?(that's not rethorical)
They are treated differently, would you allow that to happen to your daughter? Being a caricature of a <b> woman </b>by the way society shapes her? I know that for me it's not happening. If one day I have a daughter or a boy, I won't let anyone treat her or him as if she or he is less than what she or he actually is.

@Joannot
Like I said, I do also think there is a problem with women in the engineering disciplines but I don't know how to solve it.  My daughter is good at math and science so we push her more towards engineering, even though she likes music more.  But like you said, if she wants to be a musician then I won't stop her even if I want her to become an engineer.

Also, what the video said at those times have been asked to me also and I don't take it any other way than what is asked, what do you do at your job?  I have no idea why they find it offensive or puzzling, which is why I said women tend to be more sensitive then men.  Maybe they were trying to ask what kind of engineering discipline do you do?  Is that something that shouldn't be asked?  There are many types of <b> engineers,</b> especially in today's world.  Is she a mechanical engineer, electrical, chemical, computer, how am I supposed to know by the company that she tells me?
